description.text:
Replacement bracket for the z axis nut holder in a Printrbot Jr.
Reduces the amount of play the z axis nut had to a minimum.
Replaces the original threaded rod and nut with stainless steel M8 threaded rod,
two nuts and a spring in between the two nuts. Ideally you should use brass nuts.
But I used stainless steel nuts since they were available and work just fine.

1) print the two bracket halves
2) remove the original laser cut z axis nut holder assembly (save the screws, you will need the later)
3) remove the original nut and threaded rod
4) mount the M8 stainless steel threaded rod (apply a little grease to the rod, much smoother rotation possible this way)
5) screw first nut onto rod
6) place spring on top of nut
7) screw second nut onto rod until the nut-spring-nut package fits the 3d printed brackets
8) mount brackets with original screws (step 2)
9) remember to change your mm/revolution setting of your z axis in the control software of your choice. By the way, a M8 thread has a 1.25 mm pitch per revolution. *) UPDATE #1: Added Sketchup file for ease of modifying spring size or change metal parts from metric to imperial units.

comments.text:
Not to nit-pick, but you really should use an ACME threaded rod as opposed to a standard M8 thread. While the M8 rod and nuts are cheaper, they have more surface area contact with slightly wider tolerances since they are designed to be torqued down for permanent or semi-permanent installation. Eventually, this set of rod and nuts will wear on each other (especially if brass nuts are used) and result in a sloppy fit, the exact problem this is designed to solve.
Otherwise, this is a solid idea/design.
comments.author: Bleezz

comments.text:
You are absolutely right, those M8 threaded rods are not the ideal choice. Only reason I chose then is that I had them already at hand and thought that greasing them well would be enough to reduce wear. And since they are still working a treat I'm not planning on replacing them any time soon. ;-)
But if I had a bigger printer or would use it more often I would definitely pick a different thread type.

description.text: This is a 6 barrels Gatling Rubber Band Gun, capable of loading up to 48 rounds (...although it is much easier to load 30-36 rounds). It rotates using a hand crank, and fires using a thumb operated trigger. This is a big, but relatively easy print. Other than a small overhang on the handle, no other parts requires support. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=a9VI8fMDmSQ

Designed in FreeCAD (fcstd file is included) and printed in PLA using Cura. Print using the individual component's STL file, and refer to the "Assembled" and "Exploded" view to see how everything fits together. You'll need 6 pieces each of "Barrel", "Ratchet Wheel", "Ratchet Catch". For the rest of the parts, you only need 1 piece each. Besides the 3D prints, you'll also need...
  • M4x20mm screw and nut (6 pcs) (longer screws are ok)
  • M4x16mm screw and nut (6 pcs) (longer screws are ok)
  • Zip tie / Cable tie (4 pcs)
  • Rubber band (lots!)
    • Tips:
  • You may want to sand the curved surface on the "Trigger" that rubs against the "Ratchet Catch". Makes for a smoother firing.
  • The barrel should be laid diagonally across the build surface. If you do so, it should be small enough for most 3D printers to print.
  • When the gun is not loaded, the "Ratchet Wheel" can rotate freely, and may jam the "Ratchet Catch". It's harmless, but will cause the gun to feel rough if you dry fire it.
  • The STL contains some fixes and improvements over the photographed version, so don't be worried if your build does not look exactly the same as the photos.

This ukelele prints in 4 pieces and glues together with superglue.

All parts printed in PLA with 0.2mm layers.  The body prints as a single piece with no supports (all needed supports are built into the model).  The supports on the bottom breakaway, but the internal supports can be left in place.  
The fretboard and the peghead plate also print without supports.  The neck, however, needs to be printed with supports turned on.  
On the peghead plate (which is optional), you can pause the print after the first 2 payers and change filament color to get contrasting text.  
All parts glue together with superglue.  First glue the fretboard to the neck (the 12th fret should be aligned to the joint between the neck and body) and then glue the neck to the body.  Finally, glue on the peghead plate. The peghead has 10mm holes for standard miniature guitar tuners.   
After assembly, you will probably want to file notches in the saddle to lower the strings to a comfortable height.

title: Extruded filament cooler for Huxley-type extruders
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text: This thing makes it possible to cool down the printed filament so it won't go, like, blob when trying to build something that takes less than 30 seconds per layer, and it will help you building bridges.

To complete this thing you need a 40mm fan, like a chipset cooler, 6 screws, and about 20cm of 2-wire ribbon cable or 40cm normal cable or whatever to extend the coolers power cable.  
You need only two of the three wires from the cooler, have a look at RepRapPros Huxley building manual, chapter "Hot end assembly" for what to do. You can wire the two cables directly to a power source or to a special fan connector, if your printer's mainboard supports that.  
I used an Akasa AK-210 (that's the one that comes with the Huxley for its extruder, it takes the Huxleys 19V, no problem), unscrewed it from the heat sink that comes with it and reused the four screws to later fixate the cooler onto my thing. (You'll need to shorten two of them with a file or such!) Additionally, I used two short M3 screws that were leftovers from a computer.  
This thing does not need support structures to print!

description.text:
So the kid wanted to play with my swiss army knife. And of course we had to point out that it isn't exactly a toy. But then he asked, "could you make me a toy one". Well... Here's a safer swiss army knife for kids. A "blade" on the other side, a few drawing stencils on the other. Note that you can also add the name of the owner, see instructions -- discretely left that out of the model files. This isn't quite perfect, I may or may not revise it someday to fix these:
  • Stencil blade too long, one circle overlapping
  • Add holes for stoppers too
  • Add some slope to stencil holes, now you need a very sharp pencil
  • Longer poles
    • Loosely based on Swiss army style keyring, I ended up rewriting pretty much of the .scad file. But the basic idea is the same.

Print out each of the STL files, mind the orientation so that the flat side comes down.  
You can also fire up OpenSCAD, and create a file Swiss_toy_owner_name.dxf, containing the name of the owner in 2D drawing. Check the scaling in ownerName() module. Then you can just re-render the Swiss_Army2.stl and the name gets extruded on top.

I have a cnc mill see here: http://robotik.dyyyh.de/cnc.html which is rather heavy. At the time im driving it with the reprap electronix when printig. The problem is, that the acceleration and speed of the axis is controlled much better by EMC2 then the reprap electronics can do. For a normal mendel which has low mass this might be not as important, but for a heavy machine it makes a differenze. Another anoying thin is, that i have to plug the stepper-drevers to the reprap-electronix when printing, and back to the parallelport when milling.
The board will be connected to the serial port of the PC which is driving the mill and controlled by the EMC2 Axis interface with gcodes as usual.
The difference is, it uses rs232 and not rs485
The controller is an ATMega168 which makes the board compatible with the Arduino stuff..
Features:
  • 3 Temperatur sensor inputs
  • 3 FET outputs, for heater, bed or something, (bigger ones with option to mount heatsink)
  • serial port for communikation with host pc
  • isp pins for programming the uC or flahing bootloader
  • uart pins for programming with FT232 usb-seriel translator
  • i2c for whatever comunication i dont know jet
  • 4 general purpose pins with vcc/gnd for further stuff...
    • I took SMD parts only for the resistors and capacitors, because the TQFP parts are hard to solder if somebody wants to built this. There is no Stepper controller or any motor driver for the extruder on this board, cause these things can be driven from emc directly by sending step/dir signals over the parallel port (or a mesa card) the firmware for the controller and the plugin for EMC2 will follow... If you have any ideas what i could add / change on the board please let me know EDIT: i uploaded the firmware for the controller, did not really test it, only with the serial terminal, but seems to work EDIT: New tarball added.
    Tarball includes Mcodes for ExtruderTemp and FanSpeed till now,
    others will follow, (its almost the same everywhere)
    Firmware for the atmega8
    eagle files I allready connected it sucsessfully to EMC2 and printed some thing see here:
    http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_lRp1l8qiyE
etch pcb -> solder parts -> flash programm -> ... -> profit

This is my BI V2.5 Pico conversion aka the "The Batman Kit".  
This retrofit don't include a height adjustment for the nozzle. Contrary to the BI J-Head, the dimension of the Pico is amazingly accurate. For the same nozzles diameter, I get the same length as far as my caliper can measure. Anyway, the original hotend, with an o-ring, was flimsy (mine at least).  
With this conversion, there is no need to ream or dremel the plate's holes. Use what is already there.  
I've included the SolidWorks files so you can adjust the parts for your printer.

(for 1 Pico) 1 x Pico (1.75mm, Bowden Groovemount, 12V heater, optional 500°C Thermistor)
1 x 40mm Fan (came with the Pico from KS)
1 x M3x20mm screw
1 x M3 Nyloc nut
4 x M3x10mm screw
1 x 2 pair wire (for the fan), from top to effector
1 x Molex Mini-Fit Jr.™ Power Connectors w/ pins for the Pico cooler fan (56H7743/88C9490)
1 x set of Molex SL™ Modular Connectors w/ pins for the Pico cooler fan (89C1698/38C9863/97B0029/08P0700)
1 x printed batman kit (ABS)
1 x printed fan shroud (ABS) Optional: If you install more than one Pico, you'll need to buy Molex connectors accordingly. Also, if you want to cool the extruder motors with my EZStruder Mount for BI V2.5, you'll need these connectors to build a Y cable at the top: 38C9709/90B6898. *The parts number above are for the Newark reseller. You can find actual manufacturer (Molex) parts number looking at the Newark pages.

All parts MUST be printed in ABS. There is serious heat around Pico.  
For best result, print at 0.2mm layer height, 100% infill. The bats height is critical, they must fit tightly.

You need to remove the outer shrink from the Pico wires, this is needed to install the fan shroud. Take extreme care when un-heatshrinking the thermistor's wires. Mine was twisted at the base of the thermistor, I've to remove the spring and redo the soldering (it was crimped, this is the first batch of the KS campaign). There was a short-circuit there.

You simply slide the bats like this: Note the small cut in the aluminium plate that indicate the nozzle order, photo show the hotend with the Bowden plug fit in the first position. The other hotends are ordered in counterclockwise position as seen above the effector. The fins must point outward, or if you prefer, the heater cartridge near the outside perimeter: Once the Pico plate is installed underneath the effector, use the other aluminum plate to sandwitch the effector on the top side, bolt in place with socket screws. Don't forget to insert the wire into the proper holes of the plates.

Last night I broke the front hook, because I tilted the rifle too far outwards while removing to show a friend. 50% infill printed with the hook pointed up is NOT enough plastic! If used gently it can still work with the hook pointed up, but I recommend printing with supports, lying flat on the table so the layers are mostly identical, and in ABS so supports can be easily removed for maximum strength. For those interested in materials science engineering (I almost did a minor) or the study of composites, this illustrates what a difference grain direction makes for anisotropic materials. Fortunately I heard a crack of layer delamination just before failure and immediately moved my hand on the rear of the rifle upwards, so when it broke the front swung down barely missing the matching wooden nightstand! Phew! That was close, good thing I keep my display rifles unloaded and without the bayonet attached despite the temptation :D
Mount your antique WWII rifle on your wall for some historic decor with a touch of modern fabrication/prototyping techniques!

After a quick search returned not much that I was comfortable using to hang a heavy wooden rifle over/near my bed, I quickly made these.  Simple yet elegant (kinda).  Use it to mount a Mosin Nagant or other rifle or object shaped like a rifle to your wall.  I am not responsible for any injury or damages if your print or mounting option is insufficient for supporting the weight of the object you hang on it.  
Having said that, I printed mine with the hook pointing up, which is weaker than on its side for this purpose, using only 50% infill and it hasn't fallen yet.

Print both front and rear hook, the larger diameter one is for the rear which is wider.  They are designed so their center's are lined up when both mounted flush to a surface.  
I used .15mm layer, 2 shells, 50% infill, and ABS, but I would recommend more material to be safe.  Mine hasn't broken yet, however.

description.text:
These are modified printed parts for the MM2 beta kit extruder. 3 parts include filament guide, a handle extender, and support plate to snug the hot end to the extruder. What's changed:
1) On the filament guide I lowered the nipple box so it's flush against the support plate and won't twist when the spring is applied. Also, moved the nipple forward and angled top corner to allow more depression of the spring.
2) Support plate cutout for hot end was increased to be more snug. Also brought the holes in a tad so they line up with the aluminum holes better.
3) Created a handle with thumb cutout for depressing the spring when changing filament.

Printed at .25 layer, 50% infill, 2 loops.
On the filament guide, the bottom side that sits over the top screw head has a support you need to pop off before it will fit.
Also filed down a channel in the aluminum top arm for the filament.
NOTE: All parts have been printed, however, we have not acutally used the extruder yet as our RAMPS board caught fire.

I wanted a way to mount 3rd party spools on my Da Vinci Duo and found some good ideas here. I ended up printing this one: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:433194/#files I then made these guides to help guide the filament around the back of the printer and through the crack in the back cover. The pictures are a little distorted. I took them with my phone and it looks like it resized them.

I first printed the spool holder from here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:433194/#files Then printed both guides in this thing. I used 30% and .4 for a layer height and they came out nice and strong. I think I used 50% for the spool holder, can't remember. I had to clean up the holes in the guides using a 1/4" drill. I picked up some cheap tubing at Lowe's made by Watts. There are several numbers on it, 443061, LSPEB25, and 42141208. It is 1/4" OD / .170" ID (8mm OD / 5mm ID) polyethylene tubing. I think it was like $3.99 for 25 feet of the stuff! I mounted the guides using some super strong double sided tape made by 3M, also got at Lowe's. The side guide just sticks to the side of the case. Print two of these if you have the Duo. The rear guide is meant to fit right under where the stock guide tubes are. It has slots cut out to go right around them. I stuck it on using the double sided tape from the back of the machine, not from the inside. It has two holes / cylinders that stick through the gap in the back of the case and into the inside of the case. I tried to get a couple of pictures from inside the case. The stock filament guides can stay in place, no need to remove them. In the picture I still have the white filament going through the stock hole. Cut a piece of the tubing and connect the two guides. It should be just long enough to go from the one on the side, around the back, under the rear cover and into the rear guide. Thread the filament and enjoy!

Interested by the battery box design of totof1965 (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:252542) I decided to print one for my Taranis Plus. The problem was that the bottom lip was not high enough to clear the battery I was using, a Nano-Tech 2.1 LIFE, this measures 100mm x 30mm x 30mm. So I set about designing my own cover. This is the first file, the flat cover.
After this I was musing on how to mount the small LIPO battery I had for running my FPV DVR 7" screen. Out of interest the battery is Turnigy 2.2 9XR, these have built in over\under discharge protection. I though this a good idea as the DVR has no battery reading on it. But how to mount it?
This is my solution, the second file. The battery is 102mm x 33mm x 20mm and the external extension to the case just fits on their nicely. In all a rather neat solution to the problem.

The models are printed on me XYZ Davinci 1 (hacked) printer, sliced in Slic3r. I have the perimeters set to 4, print at .2 thickness and use 4mm hexagonal supports. Density is set to 20%. I recommend printing as shown in the picture, this way the locking tabs get to be printed cleanly.  
Enjoy :-)

description.text: The iPad HandleStand is a protective case that has been hacked with a pair of 3D printed handles that hinge open into an A-Frame adjustable stand. It works with a Smart Cover or with the Logitech UltraThin Keyboard Cover, and it tilts to any angle. Additional information can be found on the blog: http://interlockroc.org/2013/04/06/3d-printed-handlestand-for-ipad/

Parts list:
-(1) Hinge Set (containing 2 brackets and 4 hinge members).
-(2) Handles (each containing parts for a 3-piece handle and a MicroBeaner for the shoulder strap).
-(1) Polycarbonate iPad case that snaps on at the corners such asamazon.com/PoeticBasic-Smart-Cover-Slim-Fit-Crystal/dp/B007JBN6NQ
-(2) Stainless steel 6-32 x .75 inch oval phillips machine screw (attach hinges to brackets)
-(2) flat-head 6-32 x .5 inch machine screw (attach brackets to polycarbonate case)
-(4) 6-32 lock nuts with nylon inserts
(4) #10 o-ring provide friction for hinges
(4) #41 o-ring provide friction against a table
-(1) .125 inch parachord 5 feet long Tools:
-Drill with .125 inch bit and countersink bit
-Solvent to bond ABS such as Oatey cleaner (yellow label white can) made for ABS plumbing pipe (or use acetone or superglue)... See warning below!
-Use match or lighter to burn the cut ends of parachord WARNING:
-Use CAUTION during solvent bonding!
-Use eye protection.
-Work in well ventilated area!
-The solvent dissolves many things, and the wet plastic stains whatever it touches!
-Use latex NOT vinyl gloves!
-Use aluminum foil on work surface! Note:
-Use great care to go back and coat the whole part for a uniform glossy finish (especially if parts were sanded), but do one end and hang to dry (for a few minutes) before doing the other end!
-The solvent can also be used to heal delaminated parts, but BE CAREFUL!
